author: aron2295
body:
Honestly, I’m for putting the least amount down. 

Our PMI is $100 ~. I’ve seen it lower on a few. 

I was told it did used to be $200 - $300. 

I know you asked if there was any strategy. 

These are my thoughts:

1) Rates are low. Honestly, rates are so low, it’s warped people’s perception. From what I understand, in the 20th century, in the 80’s, rates could hit 20%. 

Inflation is 2%. 30 year fixed rate mortgages are 3% ~. If someone keeps renting, their rent will keep going up and when they leave, they own nothing. They paid someone else’s mortgage. In Every time I left an apartments, they always found something to bill you for. So, I wasn’t even living there and I had to pay them!

2) When it’s in the house, you can’t access it. We’ve gotten a lot of calls of people that want to re finance and take cash out or get a Home Equity Line of Credit (HELOC). I like to tel customers to think of their home like a savings account. But, 1) we’re not offering those right now and 2) It’s a 2nd mortgage. It’s not quick. I’m sure they would’ve spent it some other way but still. 

3) Going back to renting, around me, and this may be region specific, a one bedroom is $1000 / month. I’d rather pay $100 / month for PMI knowing every month I’m building up equity then pay $1000 / month and build up nothing. And if you want you a house, you’re still saving up for that too. 

The way I see it, the house doesn’t know how it’s being paid for and it doesn’t care. A customer is always welcome to pay extra towards the principal so this could come across as rude but if someone wants to pay the house off quickly, that’s up to them. Work a second job, move up in your field, win the lottery, again, the house does not care and we don’t have any early pay off penalties or restrictions.
